**BESTIARY OF THE ABYSS**

Creatures of the Dómnathar

*Monsters, Mutates, and Horrors of the Eleven Great Houses*

Oreka: Echoes of the Elemental Dawn

*Compatible with the d20 System (3.5 Edition)*

**Introduction: The Flesh-Forges and the Abyss Circle**

The Dómnathar do not simply wage war—they reshape life itself. Deep beneath Oreka, in the obsidian halls of Dómnathar-Zhuan and the scattered strongholds of the Wars of the Shattered Host, each Great House has cultivated its own weapons of living horror. Some are crude, mass-produced shock troops. Others are masterworks of alien sorcery that blur the line between creature and curse.

This bestiary is divided into two sections. The first presents the Buarath Mutate Family—a lineage of flesh-warped creatures produced by House Buarath’s flesh-forges under the patronage of Buaress, the Many-Mask. These range from expendable graftlings to apocalyptic abominations, and any House may commission them (at a price). The second section presents creatures unique to each of the remaining Houses and the fallen House Konaeth, each reflecting the patron deity and character of its creators.

All creatures in this document share one trait that marks them as Dómnathar-spawned: they are silent to Kin-sense. Where Orekan monsters register as discordant notes or hostile resonances, these creatures register as nothing at all—a void where life should be. This is often the first and only warning a Kin party receives before contact.

**Part One: The Buarath Mutate Family**

*"**Buarath does not create. Buarath reveals what flesh was always trying to become.**"** — Fleshweaver Zarn*

House Buarath’s patron is Buaress, the Many-Mask—god of mutation, grafting, stolen faces, and body horror. Under Buaress’s doctrine, flesh is merely unfinished clay waiting for a sculptor’s hand. The House’s flesh-forges produce a range of living weapons sold to other Houses or deployed in Buarath’s own campaigns. What follows is the standard product line, from cheapest to most catastrophic.

**Graftling**

*Small Aberration (Extraplanar) — CR 1*

Graftlings are the refuse of Buarath’s flesh-forges—failed experiments that survived the cutting table but emerged wrong. Each is a unique tangle of mismatched tissue: an arm growing from a ribcage, a cluster of eyes where a hand should be, legs of differing length that produce a lurching, uneven gait. They are not intelligent in any meaningful sense, driven instead by a dull, gnawing hunger and an instinctive loyalty to whichever Fleshweaver last fed them.

Buarath deploys them in swarms as tunnel guards and living alarms. Their value lies not in combat effectiveness but in sheer expendability—a graftling costs nothing to produce and screams loudly when it dies, alerting nearby defenders. Some Houses purchase them in bulk as disposable sentries for outlying warrens.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **2d8+2 (11 hp)

**Initiative: **+1

**Speed: **20 ft.

**AC: **13 (+1 size, +1 Dex, +1 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 12

**Attacks: **2 slams +2 melee (1d4+1) or bite +2 melee (1d3+1 plus disease)

**Special Attacks: **Disease (Forge Rot—Fort DC 12, incubation 1d3 days; 1d3 Con damage)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., DR 2/slashing, mindless hunger (immune to mind-affecting), Abyssal Silence (does not register on Kin-sense)

**Saves: **Fort +1, Ref +1, Will +3

**Abilities: **Str 12, Dex 13, Con 12, Int 1, Wis 10, Cha 3

**Skills: **Hide +7, Listen +2, Move Silently +3

**Environment: **Underground (Dómnathar warrens, flesh-forge refuse pits)

**Organization: **Solitary, pair, or swarm (4–16)

**Kin-Sense Signature: **Void (absolute silence; indistinguishable from empty space)

**Tactics**

Graftlings swarm the nearest living thing and attempt to drag it down through sheer numbers. They have no self-preservation instinct and fight until destroyed. Clever Fleshweavers sometimes pack alchemical payloads into graftling torsos—when the creature is killed, the payload ruptures (treat as splash weapon, 1d6 acid in 5-ft. radius, Ref DC 12 half).

**Facetaker**

*Medium Aberration (Extraplanar, Shapechanger) — CR 4*

Where the graftling is a failure, the Facetaker is a targeted success—a Buarath infiltrator designed for one purpose: to wear another person’s face. The process is horrifyingly literal. A Fleshweaver surgically removes a victim’s face and grafts it onto the Facetaker’s blank, featureless skull. For a period of days, the Facetaker can pass as the victim, speaking in their voice, mimicking their mannerisms (drawn from psychic residue in the harvested tissue), and even fooling magical detection short of true seeing.

The disguise is imperfect. After 1d4+2 days, the grafted face begins to rot—the seams darken, the eyes cloud, the voice thickens. Facetakers who overstay their welcome become increasingly erratic and violent as the dying tissue feeds corrupt impulses back into their brains. Experienced Buarath handlers rotate faces regularly, sometimes carrying spare faces in preservation jars.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **5d8+10 (32 hp)

**Initiative: **+6

**Speed: **30 ft.

**AC: **16 (+2 Dex, +4 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 14

**Attacks: **2 claws +6 melee (1d6+3) or by weapon +6 melee

**Special Attacks: **Face Rip (grapple; if pinned for 2 rounds, removes victim’s face—1d6 Con damage, permanent disfigurement; Fort DC 14 or stunned 1d4 rounds from pain)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., Stolen Face (as disguise self but physical, +10 to Disguise; degrades after 1d4+2 days), psychic echo (gains +4 to Bluff checks to impersonate the face’s owner), Abyssal Silence, light sensitivity

**Saves: **Fort +3, Ref +3, Will +5

**Abilities: **Str 16, Dex 15, Con 14, Int 11, Wis 12, Cha 8 (Cha 14 while wearing a fresh face)

**Skills: **Bluff +8 (+12 with fresh face), Disguise +8 (+18 with Stolen Face), Hide +8, Move Silently +8, Listen +6, Sense Motive +6

**Environment: **Any (deployed behind enemy lines)

**Organization: **Solitary or cell (1 Facetaker + 1d4 Shadeblades as handlers)

**Kin-Sense Signature: **Void (the stolen face does not generate Kin resonance; perceptive Kin may notice the “silence” where a friend should ring)

**Tactics**

Facetakers avoid direct combat. Their mission is infiltration—replace a key figure, gather intelligence, then either sabotage or assassinate at the optimal moment. If exposed, they fight with desperate ferocity, attempting to grapple and rip the face of the most important-looking opponent as both weapon and escape route. A Facetaker with a fresh face and time to prepare is one of the most dangerous low-CR threats in the Dómnathar arsenal.

**Fleshwrought**

*Large Aberration (Extraplanar) — CR 7*

The Fleshwrought is Buarath’s main line of battle—a purpose-built war-mutant assembled from multiple donors and reinforced with bone plating, redundant organs, and weaponized limbs. Each stands seven to eight feet tall, armored in ridged bone that grows directly from the musculature. They typically sport two primary combat limbs (fused bone-blade arms or oversized crushing fists) and one or two vestigial limbs that serve secondary functions—holding shields, carrying supplies, or grasping terrain during climbs.

Unlike graftlings, Fleshwroughts retain a cruel, limited intelligence. They understand Dómnathar commands and can execute simple tactical plans: hold this corridor, kill everything that enters, advance on signal. They feel no pain—a deliberate modification—and will continue fighting with shattered limbs and exposed organs until the central nerve cluster (buried deep in the torso) is destroyed.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **9d8+45 (85 hp)

**Initiative: **+0

**Speed: **30 ft.

**AC: **20 (–1 size, +11 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 20

**Attacks: **2 bone-blade arms +12 melee (2d6+6/19–20) or slam +12 melee (1d8+6)

**Special Attacks: **Rend (if both bone-blades hit same target, 2d6+9 additional damage), Visceral Burst (when reduced below 20 hp, all creatures within 10 ft. must save vs. Fort DC 19 or be nauseated 1d4 rounds from erupting viscera)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 90 ft., DR 5/slashing, immunity to pain effects and fear, fast healing 2, redundant organs (25% chance to negate critical hits and sneak attacks), Abyssal Silence, light sensitivity

**Saves: **Fort +8, Ref +3, Will +6

**Abilities: **Str 22, Dex 10, Con 20, Int 5, Wis 10, Cha 3

**Skills: **Climb +10, Listen +4, Spot +4

**Feats: **Improved Critical (bone-blade), Power Attack, Cleave

**Environment: **Underground (Dómnathar tunnel-war fronts)

**Organization: **Solitary, pair, or war-line (3–8, often with 1 Fleshweaver handler)

**Kin-Sense Signature: **Void (a walking emptiness that Kin describe as “a hole shaped like violence”)

**Tactics**

Fleshwroughts are deployed as shock infantry in tunnel warfare. They advance in tight corridors where their size and reach dominate, using Power Attack liberally since they cannot feel the consequences of overextension. Handlers direct them via command words shouted in Dómnathar; without guidance, they default to “kill everything that isn’t Dómnathar.” The Visceral Burst is not intentional—it’s a design flaw the Fleshweavers haven’t bothered to fix, since the eruption benefits Buarath forces (who are trained to expect it).

**Fleshweaver Adept**

*Medium Aberration (Extraplanar) — CR 10*

Not every product of the flesh-forges is a mindless weapon. The Fleshweaver Adepts are Buarath’s surgeons—former Dómnathar (or occasionally gifted Half-Dómnathar) who have undergone voluntary mutation to better serve Buaress. Each Adept has replaced at least one limb with a surgical tool-arm: bone saws, injector needles, grasping tentacles lined with sensory cilia. Their eyes have been modified to perceive the “flesh-map”—an ability to see the internal structure of living creatures through skin and armor.

Fleshweaver Adepts serve dual roles: battlefield surgeon and combat controller. They repair damaged Fleshwroughts mid-fight, graft emergency modifications onto allies, and use their surgical knowledge offensively—targeting joints, nerve clusters, and organ systems with horrifying precision. They are also the ones who create new mutates, spending weeks or months in the flesh-forges assembling each Fleshwrought or Facetaker from harvested components.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **12d8+36 (90 hp)

**Initiative: **+3

**Speed: **30 ft.

**AC: **19 (+3 Dex, +6 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 16

**Attacks: **Surgical tentacle +12 melee touch (1d6+2 plus Anatomical Strike) and bone-saw arm +12 melee (1d8+2/18–20)

**Special Attacks: **Anatomical Strike (on successful touch attack, choose one: Sever Tendon—target’s speed halved for 1d4 rounds, Fort DC 19 negates; Nerve Spike—target is staggered 1 round, no save; Organ Rupture—as a full-round action on a grappled target, 4d6 damage bypassing DR, Fort DC 19 or stunned 1 round)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 90 ft., Flesh-Map Vision (as deathwatch at will plus can identify weak points—+2 insight bonus to confirm critical hits), field surgery (can restore 2d8+10 hp to any Buarath mutate as a full-round action, 3/day), Abyssal Silence, SR 18, light sensitivity

**Spells: **Casts as 7th-level Cleric (domains: Destruction, Healing—twisted toward flesh manipulation). DC 14 + spell level. Typical prepared: cure serious wounds, bestow curse, contagion, inflict critical wounds, animate dead (using flesh-forge components)

**Saves: **Fort +7, Ref +7, Will +10

**Abilities: **Str 14, Dex 16, Con 16, Int 18, Wis 18, Cha 10

**Skills: **Heal +19, Knowledge (anatomy/arcana) +16, Concentration +15, Hide +10, Listen +12, Spot +12

**Environment: **Underground (flesh-forge laboratories, field hospitals)

**Organization: **Solitary or workshop (1 Adept + 2d4 Fleshwroughts + 1d6 Graftlings)

**Kin-Sense Signature: **Void (a “sterile” silence that Kin describe as “like standing in a room where something just died”)

**Tactics**

Adepts stay behind their Fleshwrought screen, healing and buffing their creations while casting offensive spells at priority targets. If forced into melee, they use Anatomical Strike to cripple opponents—hamstringing fighters, stunning spellcasters with nerve spikes. They always have an escape route planned and will sacrifice any number of mutates to preserve themselves, since they represent years of training and irreplaceable surgical knowledge.

**Buaressyn Abomination**

*Huge Aberration (Extraplanar) — CR 13*

The Buaressyn Abomination is a masterwork—the ultimate expression of Buaress’s doctrine that flesh is merely unfinished potential. It is not one creature but many, fused into a single howling gestalt. A typical Abomination incorporates between six and twelve donor bodies, their bones restructured into an internal scaffold, their musculature rewoven into a locomotive mass that shifts between bipedal, quadrupedal, and serpentine movement depending on terrain. Faces stud its surface—some screaming, some weeping, some locked in expressions of transcendent agony. Each retains a fragment of its original consciousness, creating a chorus of half-thoughts that the Abomination processes as a form of distributed intelligence.

Creating an Abomination requires months of work by a senior Fleshweaver and the direct blessing of Buaress—a ritual that opens the Many-Mask’s attention and pours a sliver of divine mutation-essence into the assemblage. The result is not merely alive but spiritually active: the Abomination radiates a palpable aura of wrongness that affects even non-Kin creatures. Dómnathar themselves find Abominations unsettling, which Buarath considers a feature. Only Buarath the Many-Faced—himself a mass of grafted flesh and eyes—is said to find them beautiful.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **16d8+112 (184 hp)

**Initiative: **+1

**Speed: **40 ft., climb 20 ft.

**AC: **24 (–2 size, +1 Dex, +15 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 23

**Attacks: **4 limb-strikes +18 melee (2d6+8) and bite +16 melee (2d8+4 plus grab)

**Space/Reach: **15 ft./15 ft.

**Special Attacks: **Improved Grab, Absorb (on successful grapple, begins fusing target into its mass—1d6 Con drain per round; if target reaches 0 Con, permanently absorbed; Fort DC 25 each round to resist drain), Chorus of Anguish (all creatures within 30 ft. must save vs. Will DC 22 or be shaken for 1d6 rounds; those who fail by 5+ are frightened; mind-affecting, sonic)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 120 ft., DR 10/magic and slashing, fast healing 5, immunity to pain and fear, SR 22, redundant organs (50% chance to negate critical hits and sneak attacks), all-around vision (cannot be flanked), regenerative adaptation (after taking 50+ fire damage in a single encounter, gains fire resistance 10 for remainder of encounter; similarly for cold, acid, electricity), Abyssal Silence

**Saves: **Fort +12, Ref +6, Will +12

**Abilities: **Str 26, Dex 12, Con 24, Int 8, Wis 14, Cha 6

**Skills: **Climb +16, Listen +12, Spot +12 (+16 vs. flanking due to all-around vision)

**Feats: **Multiattack, Power Attack, Cleave, Great Cleave, Improved Bull Rush, Awesome Blow

**Environment: **Underground (released only for major assaults or as area-denial weapons)

**Organization: **Solitary (always; they do not tolerate each other) or accompanied by 1 Fleshweaver Adept handler

**Kin-Sense Signature: **Screaming Void (not merely silent but actively disruptive; Kin within 60 ft. suffer –2 penalty to Kin-sense checks as their resonance is drowned out by the Abomination’s spiritual static)

**Tactics**

An Abomination is a siege weapon. It is released into enemy tunnels or fortifications and left to do what it does: advance, absorb, grow. It prioritizes grappling over killing, attempting to drag victims into its mass where the Absorb ability does the real work. Handlers stay well back and use prearranged signal-horns to direct it toward priority targets. If an Abomination absorbs enough victims during a single engagement (roughly six or more Medium creatures), it enters a frenzy of growth that temporarily increases its size to Gargantuan and adds +2 to all physical ability scores for 1d4 hours—at which point even its handlers begin to worry.

**Part Two: Creatures of the Great Houses**

Each Great House has cultivated creatures that reflect its patron deity, its cultural obsessions, and its preferred methods of war. Unlike the Buarath mutates—which are manufactured—many of these are summoned, bred, or cursed into existence through rituals unique to each House’s tradition. What follows is one signature creature per House, representing the most commonly encountered (or most feared) product of that House’s particular brand of horror.

**Gazebound**

*Medium Outsider (Extraplanar, Evil) — CR 5*

*House Vaalor — Patron: Oczur-Vaal, the One Gaze*

The Gazebound are eyeless executioner-fiends summoned by House Vaalor’s priesthood. Each is a tall, gaunt humanoid figure wrapped in black silk, its face a smooth expanse of obsidian-dark skin with no features at all—no eyes, no mouth, no nose. A single vertical seam runs from forehead to chin. When the Gazebound is commanded to kill, the seam splits open to reveal a single enormous eye—burning amber, slitted like a cat’s—that carries a lethal fragment of Oczur-Vaal’s killing gaze.

Gazebound are used as executioners, not soldiers. Vaalor dispatches them to eliminate specific targets: traitors, rival House scions marked for death, or surfacer leaders who have become inconvenient. They arrive silently, open their eye, and leave. The body is found later with no wounds—just an expression of absolute terror and burst blood vessels behind the eyes.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **6d8+12 (39 hp)

**AC: **18 (+2 Dex, +6 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 16

**Attacks: **2 claws +8 melee (1d6+2)

**Special Attacks: **Death Gaze (30 ft. cone when seam opens; all creatures in cone must save Will DC 16 or take 3d6 damage and be paralyzed 1 round; those who fail by 10+ must also save Fort DC 16 or die; gaze can be opened as a standard action, usable 3/day), Fear Aura (20 ft., Will DC 15 or shaken, continuous while eye is open)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 120 ft., blindsight 60 ft. (tremorsense and sound), DR 5/good, SR 16, Abyssal Silence, immune to gaze attacks and visual effects (eyeless until activated)

**Saves: **Fort +7, Ref +7, Will +7

**Abilities: **Str 14, Dex 15, Con 14, Int 10, Wis 14, Cha 16

**Environment: **Any (dispatched from Dómnathar-Zhuan to specific targets)

**Organization: **Solitary (always; Vaalor sends one per target)

**Mirrorskin**

*Medium Outsider (Extraplanar, Evil, Shapechanger) — CR 6*

*House Aelathar — Patron: Vaelissar, the Gilded Rot*

Mirrorskins are desire-fiends bred in Aelathar’s pleasure palaces—creatures that do not have a true form. Instead, a Mirrorskin reflexively assumes the shape of whatever its viewer most desires: a lost lover, a childhood friend, an idealized version of the viewer themselves. This is not illusion magic but genuine shapeshifting driven by a low-level psychic read. The effect is deeply personal and varies per observer; in a group, each person sees a different shape, though only the Mirrorskin’s primary target gets the full effect.

The seduction is both emotional and metabolic. Proximity to a Mirrorskin produces a euphoric warmth—a sense of being utterly loved and understood—that is in fact a slow-acting venom. Victims who linger too long find their will eroded, their judgment clouded, and their bodies weakened as the Mirrorskin feeds on their life force through skin contact. Aelathar uses them as honeypots, planting Mirrorskins near enemy leaders and waiting for the target to waste away.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **7d8+14 (45 hp)

**AC: **17 (+3 Dex, +4 natural), touch 13, flat-footed 14

**Attacks: **Touch +8 melee (1d4 Wisdom drain)

**Special Attacks: **Heart’s Mirror (supernatural; each creature within 30 ft. must Will DC 17 or perceive the Mirrorskin as their deepest desire; affected creatures cannot attack the Mirrorskin and take –4 to saves against its other abilities; broken by damage or a successful second save), Draining Touch (1d4 Wis drain on touch; victim is unaware of drain while under Heart’s Mirror), Gilded Kiss (if Mirrorskin successfully drains 6+ Wis from a single target, that target becomes permanently charmed as dominate person, CL 10th, Will DC 17)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., DR 5/cold iron, SR 17, shapeshifting (as alter self at will, but appearance is determined by viewer’s psyche, not Mirrorskin’s choice), Abyssal Silence, immune to charm and compulsion

**Saves: **Fort +4, Ref +8, Will +8

**Abilities: **Str 10, Dex 17, Con 14, Int 14, Wis 16, Cha 20

**Environment: **Any (typically placed in locations where targets will encounter them “naturally”)

**Organization: **Solitary (exposure to multiple Mirrorskins causes psychic interference; Aelathar never deploys more than one per operation)

**Blessed Hollow**

*Large Aberration (Extraplanar) — CR 8*

*House Domnethra — Patron: Myrnaazhul, the Abyssal Womb*

The Blessed Hollows are walking brood-vessels—massively distended humanoid figures whose torsos have been hollowed out and consecrated as mobile wombs of Myrnaazhul. They were once living Dómnathar or captured Kin, transformed through a weeks-long ritual of forced feeding, surgical expansion, and divine investiture until the original person is gone and only the Hollow remains: a lurching, moaning vessel that endlessly births lesser horrors from its gaping abdominal cavity.

Domnethra deploys Blessed Hollows as area-denial weapons and breeding platforms. A single Hollow released into an enemy settlement will produce a steady stream of Womb-Spawn—small, vicious creatures that swarm and overwhelm defenders—until the Hollow itself is destroyed. The spawn are not true creatures but temporary manifestations of Myrnaazhul’s hunger, dissolving into rancid fluid within hours of the Hollow’s death.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **10d8+50 (95 hp)

**AC: **17 (–1 size, +8 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 17

**Attacks: **2 bloated arms +11 melee (1d8+5)

**Special Attacks: **Birth Swarm (as a standard action, the Hollow births 1d4 Womb-Spawn into adjacent squares; see below for Spawn stats; can birth a maximum of 20 Spawn per day), Agonized Wail (60 ft. burst, all living creatures Will DC 20 or sickened 1d4 rounds; on a natural 1, also nauseated 1 round; sonic, mind-affecting)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., DR 5/good, fast healing 3 (increases to fast healing 5 if any Womb-Spawn are alive within 100 ft.; they feed it through sympathetic connection), Abyssal Silence, immune to pain and mind-affecting effects

**Saves: **Fort +8, Ref +3, Will +9

**Abilities: **Str 20, Dex 8, Con 20, Int 2, Wis 14, Cha 4

**Environment: **Underground or deployed into enemy territory

**Organization: **Solitary + 4d6 active Womb-Spawn

**Womb-Spawn (CR 1/2)**

** **Tiny Aberration; HD 1d8 (4 hp); AC 14; Speed 40 ft.; Attack: bite +4 melee (1d3–1 plus attach); Special: Attach (on hit, automatically deals 1 damage/round until removed; Str DC 10 to pull off); dissolves 1d4 hours after Hollow’s death.

**Screamblade Serpent**

*Large Construct (Extraplanar) — CR 9*

*House Tethrakh — Patron: Tethzhaar, the Iron Serpent*

Tethrakh’s demon-forges do not merely produce weapons—they produce beings that are weapons. The Screamblade Serpent is the most feared: a fifteen-foot serpentine construct of interlocking venomous iron plates, animated by the bound soul of a sentient being (usually a captured enemy or a disobedient slave). The soul provides the animating will; the iron provides the killing power. The name comes from the sound it makes—a continuous, metallic shrieking as its plates grind against each other, audible from hundreds of feet away in tunnel environments.

The trapped soul is fully conscious but unable to control the body. It can only scream—hence the sound. Tethrakh considers this a feature: the sonic assault is as much a weapon as the physical body, and the psychological horror of recognizing a friend’s voice in the shrieking has broken more than one defensive line.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **12d10+30 (96 hp)

**AC: **23 (–1 size, +14 natural), touch 9, flat-footed 23

**Speed: **40 ft., burrow 20 ft. (through loose stone and earth only)

**Attacks: **Bite +17 melee (2d8+7 plus venom) and tail slap +12 melee (1d8+3)

**Special Attacks: **Venom (Injury, Fort DC 18; initial 1d6 Str, secondary 2d6 Str; the venom is liquid iron that hardens in the bloodstream), Constrict (2d6+10, on successful grapple), Perpetual Scream (all creatures within 60 ft. must save Will DC 18 or be shaken; those within 20 ft. who fail are deafened for 1d4 rounds; sonic)

**Special Qualities: **Construct traits, darkvision 90 ft., DR 10/adamantine, hardness 10, immunity to magic (as iron golem—fire slows, electricity heals), Abyssal Silence (to Kin-sense only; the physical screaming is very much audible), Trapped Soul (can be freed by break enchantment or miracle cast on the serpent’s remains; freed soul may provide information)

**Saves: **Fort +4, Ref +4, Will +6

**Abilities: **Str 24, Dex 10, Con —, Int — (soul is Int 12 but cannot act), Wis 14, Cha 1

**Environment: **Underground (Tethrakh tunnel-war operations, demon-forge guardians)

**Organization: **Solitary or forge-pair (2, flanking a corridor)

**Stormborn Ravager**

*Medium Outsider (Extraplanar, Evil, Chaotic) — CR 6*

*House Morkath — Patron: Morkhaz, the Red Tempest*

The Stormborn are what happens when Morkath’s blood-madness is given divine sanction. They are the bastard offspring of Morkath warriors who coupled during berserk storm-rituals—conceived in violence, born screaming, and raised in fighting pits. By adulthood, a Stormborn has been so saturated with Morkhaz’s essence that lightning arcs between their teeth when they snarl and their blood evaporates into crimson mist on contact with air.

They are not controllable in any meaningful sense. Morkath handlers simply point them at the enemy and get out of the way. A Stormborn in full frenzy is a localized weather event—rain of blood, howling winds, and continuous lightning discharges that strike friend and foe alike. Morkath considers collateral damage proof of Morkhaz’s joy.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **8d8+24 (60 hp)

**AC: **17 (+2 Dex, +5 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 15

**Attacks: **2 claws +12 melee (1d8+4 plus 1d6 electricity) or greataxe +12/+7 melee (1d12+6)

**Special Attacks: **Storm Frenzy (enter as free action; +4 Str, +4 Con, –2 AC, cannot end voluntarily; lasts until all enemies are dead or Stormborn drops; while frenzied, all melee attacks deal +1d6 electricity and each hit releases a secondary arc—10 ft., Ref DC 17, 2d6 electricity to nearest creature other than target), Blood Rain (when Stormborn takes 20+ damage from a single attack, all creatures within 15 ft. are drenched in electrified blood—2d6 electricity, Ref DC 17 half)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., electricity immunity, cold resistance 10, DR 5/lawful, Abyssal Silence, fast healing 1 (only during Storm Frenzy)

**Saves: **Fort +9, Ref +8, Will +3

**Abilities: **Str 18, Dex 15, Con 16, Int 6, Wis 8, Cha 12

**Environment: **Any (released ahead of Morkath warbands)

**Organization: **Solitary, pair, or storm-pack (3–6, which is genuinely terrifying)

**Iron Revenant**

*Medium Undead (Extraplanar) — CR 5*

*House Indorach — No single patron; tradition of disciplined war*

Indorach does not waste soldiers—not even dead ones. The Iron Revenant is a slave-soldier who has been killed, ritually preserved, and reanimated through a process that binds the corpse’s residual muscle memory to an iron framework bolted directly to the skeleton. The result is not a shambling zombie but a rigid, mechanically precise combatant that fights exactly as it did in life—executing drill formations, holding shield walls, and responding to bugle commands—because its body literally cannot move in any other way.

Iron Revenants are Indorach’s answer to attrition. A slave army that took casualties yesterday can be back at full strength tomorrow, its dead members bolted back together and marched into the same formation they died in. The psychological effect on enemies facing the same soldiers they killed the day before is substantial.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **6d12 (39 hp)

**AC: **19 (+7 armor [iron framework], +2 heavy shield), touch 10, flat-footed 19

**Attacks: **Longsword +6 melee (1d8+3) or formation thrust +6 melee (1d8+3, reach 10 ft. with longspear in second rank)

**Special Attacks: **Formation Fighting (when 3+ Iron Revenants are adjacent, they gain +2 shield bonus to AC and +1 to attack rolls; this stacks up to +4/+2 for formations of 8+), Dread Recognition (living creatures who previously killed this specific Revenant must Will DC 14 or be shaken for 1d4 rounds upon recognizing it)

**Special Qualities: **Undead traits, darkvision 60 ft., DR 5/bludgeoning, Abyssal Silence, iron-bound (cannot be turned or rebuked; the iron framework overrides divine channeling), Formation Lock (cannot be tripped, bull-rushed, or moved against its will while adjacent to another Iron Revenant)

**Saves: **Fort +2, Ref +2, Will +5

**Abilities: **Str 16, Dex 10, Con —, Int —, Wis 10, Cha 1

**Environment: **Any (wherever Indorach’s legions march)

**Organization: **Squad (4–8), company (20–40), or legion (100+, with living Indorach officers)

**Oracle Spinner**

*Large Magical Beast (Extraplanar) — CR 7*

*House Kethloryn — Patron: Ssyraeth, the Venom-Seer*

Oracle Spinners are enormous spiders—six feet at the body, twelve at the leg-span—bred in Kethloryn’s venom-temples as living prophetic instruments. Their silk is hallucinogenic: woven into specific geometric patterns, it produces visions in anyone who looks at it. Kethloryn’s mad oracle-matrons read these visions as divine messages from Ssyraeth. The spiders themselves are eerily intelligent and seem to weave with deliberate intent, though whether they are truly prophetic or merely producing random patterns that insane priestesses interpret as prophecy is a question no one in Kethloryn dares ask.

In combat, Oracle Spinners are ambush predators that use their hallucinogenic silk offensively—enshrouding victims in webs that produce terrifying, disorienting visions while the spider’s venomous bite does the real killing. Kethloryn deploys them as both guardians and intelligence assets, reading the patterns of webs spun in enemy territory for tactical guidance.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **8d10+24 (68 hp)

**AC: **18 (–1 size, +3 Dex, +6 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 15

**Speed: **40 ft., climb 30 ft.

**Attacks: **Bite +11 melee (1d8+4 plus venom)

**Special Attacks: **Venom (Injury, Fort DC 17; initial 1d4 Wis, secondary 1d4 Wis plus confused for 1d4 rounds; if Wis reaches 0, victim enters permanent hallucinatory state), Prophetic Web (60 ft. range, ranged touch +10; entangled target must Will DC 17 or suffer hallucinatory visions—as phantasmal killer but non-lethal: Will DC 17 to disbelieve, then Fort DC 17 or stunned 1d4 rounds and frightened 1d6 rounds), Web (as monstrous spider)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 60 ft., tremorsense 60 ft., DR 5/cold iron, Abyssal Silence, Webs of Foresight (Oracle Spinner is never surprised and gains +4 insight bonus to initiative; allies within 30 ft. of its web gain +2 to initiative)

**Saves: **Fort +9, Ref +9, Will +5

**Abilities: **Str 18, Dex 17, Con 16, Int 8, Wis 16, Cha 10

**Environment: **Underground (Kethloryn venom-temples, tunnel junctions rigged with prophetic webs)

**Organization: **Solitary or nest (2–4 plus 1 Kethloryn priestess handler)

**Gilded Corpse**

*Medium Undead (Extraplanar) — CR 4*

*House Bressarai — Patron: Vaelissar, the Gilded Rot*

Where Aelathar’s Mirrorskins seduce the living, Bressarai’s Gilded Corpses are the aftermath of seduction taken to its conclusion. A Gilded Corpse is a victim of Bressarai’s exquisite poisons—killed so artfully that the body shows no sign of violence, then preserved and animated through a ritual that coats it in a thin film of alchemical gold. The result is heartbreakingly beautiful: a perfect, golden figure that moves with fluid grace and kills with a touch that delivers the same poison that created it.

Bressarai uses Gilded Corpses as bodyguards, art installations, and assassins. A favorite tactic is to gift one to a rival House leader as a “statue”—which activates when a command word is spoken, or simply when it detects an opportunity. The most famous Gilded Corpses are displayed in Bressarai’s Gallery of the Golden Dead, a hall of hundreds of gleaming figures, each a former rival or enemy preserved at the peak of their beauty.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **5d12 (32 hp)

**AC: **17 (+2 Dex, +5 natural [gold coating]), touch 12, flat-footed 15

**Attacks: **2 golden touch +5 melee touch (1d4 plus Golden Venom)

**Special Attacks: **Golden Venom (contact, Fort DC 15; initial 1d4 Cha, secondary 1d4 Con; victims who die from the venom slowly turn golden over 24 hours, becoming raw material for new Gilded Corpses), Exquisite Stillness (can remain perfectly motionless indefinitely; Spot DC 25 to distinguish from a statue while inactive)

**Special Qualities: **Undead traits, darkvision 60 ft., DR 5/bludgeoning, Abyssal Silence, Golden Sheen (the gold coating reflects light-based attacks; gains +4 to saves vs. light and pattern spells), Turn Resistance +4 (the gold coating disrupts divine channeling)

**Saves: **Fort +1, Ref +3, Will +5

**Abilities: **Str 14, Dex 15, Con —, Int 6, Wis 12, Cha 16

**Environment: **Any (Bressarai strongholds, gifted to unsuspecting recipients)

**Organization: **Solitary, pair, or gallery (6–12 in a Bressarai collection)

**Dirge-Walker**

*Medium Outsider (Extraplanar, Evil, Cold) — CR 8*

*House Lokhlannar — Patron: Lokhruun, the Winter Dirge*

Dirge-Walkers are frost demons summoned from wherever Lokhruun’s frozen domain intersects with the spaces between worlds. They appear as tall, thin figures made of black ice—translucent enough to see a dim, struggling light within, which is the consumed soul that powers them. They do not walk so much as glide, leaving a trail of frost that kills small plants and freezes standing water. The air around them drops to killing cold, and their touch does not merely freeze flesh but freezes the soul, leaving the body alive but empty—a breathing husk with no personality, no memory, and no will.

Lokhlannar deploys Dirge-Walkers as terror weapons and intelligence-denial tools. A soul-frozen victim cannot be interrogated, resurrected, or spoken with via speak with dead. The soul is trapped inside the Dirge-Walker, adding to its power; a Dirge-Walker that has consumed multiple souls grows visibly brighter and more dangerous.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **10d8+30 (75 hp)

**AC: **20 (+2 Dex, +8 natural), touch 12, flat-footed 18

**Speed: **30 ft. (glide; does not trigger pressure plates or leave tracks)

**Attacks: **2 ice-claws +13 melee (1d8+3 plus 1d6 cold plus Soul Freeze)

**Special Attacks: **Soul Freeze (on hit, Fort DC 20 or take 1d4 Cha drain; if Cha reaches 0, victim’s soul is consumed and body becomes an empty husk—alive but catatonic, cannot be raised or resurrected until soul is freed), Aura of Despair (30 ft.; all creatures Will DC 18 or take –2 to attack rolls, saves, and skill checks; those who fail by 5+ are also slowed as the spell for 1d4 rounds; stacks with shaken/frightened)

**Special Qualities: **Darkvision 120 ft., DR 10/good and fire, cold immunity, fire vulnerability, SR 19, Abyssal Silence, Soul Collection (each consumed soul grants the Dirge-Walker +5 temporary hp and +1 to save DCs, to a maximum of +5 souls/+25 hp/+5 DCs), Trackless Passage (leaves no tracks, scent, or thermal signature)

**Saves: **Fort +10, Ref +9, Will +10

**Abilities: **Str 16, Dex 14, Con 16, Int 12, Wis 16, Cha 18

**Environment: **Any cold, or underground (Lokhlannar strongholds, deployed into enemy territory)

**Organization: **Solitary or dirge-pair (2, often sent to eliminate high-value targets)

**Chain Haunt**

*Large Undead (Extraplanar) — CR 6*

*House Firvarg — Patron: Firkaan, the Shackler King*

Chain Haunts are the spiritual residue of slaves who died in Firvarg’s pits—not quite ghosts, not quite constructs. When a slave dies in the iron collars and chains that Firvarg uses, and if that slave’s will was sufficiently broken before death, the despair and submission imprinted on the metal animates it. The chains rise, knotting and weaving into a vaguely humanoid mass with the dead slave’s broken psyche as its animating force. It does not remember who it was. It knows only one imperative: bind others, drag them down, make them feel what it felt.

Firvarg uses Chain Haunts as slave-catchers and perimeter guards. They are drawn to the sound of free movement—running feet, unshackled hands—and will pursue relentlessly until they have bound their quarry or been destroyed. A captured victim is dragged back toward the nearest Dómnathar outpost, still alive and increasingly terrified.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **8d12 (52 hp)

**AC: **18 (–1 size, +9 natural [iron chains]), touch 9, flat-footed 18

**Speed: **30 ft.

**Attacks: **2 chain-lash +9 melee (1d8+4 plus Binding Strike) and slam +4 melee (1d6+2)

**Reach: **15 ft. (chain-lash)

**Special Attacks: **Binding Strike (on hit, target must Ref DC 16 or be entangled; entangled targets are dragged 5 ft. toward the Chain Haunt at the start of each of its turns; Str DC 18 or Escape Artist DC 20 to break free), Enslaving Grasp (grappled creatures must Will DC 16 each round or become docile and unresisting, as if under calm emotions but specific to submission; effect ends 1d4 rounds after release)

**Special Qualities: **Undead traits, darkvision 60 ft., DR 5/—, Abyssal Silence, Chain Body (immune to piercing weapons; slashing deals half damage; vulnerable to shatter and rust effects), Freedom Sense (detects any creature moving freely within 120 ft.; cannot be fooled by invisibility but can be bypassed by immobility)

**Saves: **Fort +2, Ref +2, Will +8

**Abilities: **Str 18, Dex 10, Con —, Int 3, Wis 14, Cha 14

**Environment: **Underground (Firvarg slave routes, perimeter of Dómnathar outposts)

**Organization: **Solitary, pair, or slave-chain (3–6, usually guarding a specific corridor or approach)

**Crystal Revenant**

*Medium Undead (Extraplanar, Earth) — CR 10*

*House Konaeth (Fallen) — The Shattered Twelfth House*

When House Konaeth collapsed in the Shattering, their obsidian fortresses on the Black Isles didn’t simply crumble—they exploded into jagged crystal shards that impaled everything nearby. The Konaeth nobles who survived the initial blast were not so lucky: the living crystal that had been their House’s signature weapon grew into their bodies, replacing bone with obsidian lattice and blood with liquid crystal. They did not die. They could not die. The crystal sustains them in a state between life and undeath, fully conscious, fully aware, and in unending agony.

Three centuries later, Crystal Revenants still wander the ruins of the Black Isles and occasionally break free into the wider tunnels. Each retains the intelligence and skills it had in life—many were warriors, mages, or nobles of considerable ability—but their sanity has been eroded by centuries of crystalline agony into something alien and unpredictable. Some seek to rebuild Konaeth. Some seek to destroy every other House. Some simply kill anything they encounter to share their suffering. All are extremely dangerous.

**Abbreviated Statistics**

**Hit Dice: **12d12+24 (102 hp)

**AC: **22 (+2 Dex, +10 natural [crystal-fused body]), touch 12, flat-footed 20

**Speed: **30 ft.

**Attacks: **2 crystal-blade arms +14 melee (2d6+5/18–20 plus Crystal Infection) or crystalline burst +14 ranged touch (60 ft., 4d6 piercing)

**Special Attacks: **Crystal Infection (on critical hit, Fort DC 20 or target begins crystallizing—1d2 Dex damage per round until cured by remove curse CL 12+ or heal; if Dex reaches 0, target is permanently encased in crystal, alive and conscious), Shatter Pulse (1/day, 30 ft. burst: 8d6 piercing to all creatures, Ref DC 20 half; also functions as shatter on objects and crystalline creatures in range)

**Special Qualities: **Undead traits, darkvision 120 ft., DR 10/adamantine, SR 20, Abyssal Silence, Crystal Body (immune to cold; fire deals +50% damage; sonic attacks bypass DR), Regeneration 5 (only adamantine deals normal damage; severed limbs regrow as crystal), Fractured Sanity (immune to mind-affecting effects; however, each round in combat there is a 10% chance the Revenant stops attacking for 1 round as contradictory personalities surface)

**Saves: **Fort +4, Ref +6, Will +10

**Abilities: **Str 20, Dex 14, Con —, Int 14, Wis 14, Cha 16

**Skills: **Knowledge (arcana) +12, Listen +12, Spot +12, Intimidate +14, Hide +10 (in crystal/obsidian environments +20)

**Environment: **Black Isles ruins, deep tunnels, occasionally surfacing near shattered gate sites

**Organization: **Solitary or shard-band (2–4 with divergent agendas, making them unpredictable even as a group)

**Campaign Notes**

Crystal Revenants are unique among Dómnathar creatures in that they are not controlled by any active House. They are wild agents—remnants of a catastrophe that the other Houses prefer to pretend never happened. A Crystal Revenant might be an enemy, a reluctant ally against a common foe, or a source of lost Konaeth knowledge. Some carry memories of the Shattering that other Houses would kill to suppress. A few may even remember the original transit through the Assault Gate, making them among the oldest living (in a sense) Dómnathar in Oreka.

